{
  "answer": "In Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation Vol. III*, the chapter on military aristocracy (\"aristocratie militaire\") is Chapter 33.[^1]\n\nIts central claim regarding the military aristocracy's relation to the rest of the social order is that the governing fraction—composed of the military aristocracy—claims for itself, by right of conquest, the exclusive right to all property, while treating the governed fraction (the industrious class and broader population) only as a passive instrument of its enjoyments.[^2]\n\nThis dynamic stems from an initial division of society into a small, strongly organized military aristocracy and a large, unorganized populace lacking power, which incoming conquerors (e.g., Turks) simply join to exploit further.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL III*, ch. 33, [translation](https://falsafa.corpus/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iii-ca589a/33-des-relations-observees-entre-l-aristocratie-milit/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL III*, ch. 33, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iii-ca589a/33-des-relations-observees-entre-l-aristocratie-milit/translation/#p-0e7e56).\n\n[^3]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL III*, ch. 33, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iii-ca589a/33-des-relations-observees-entre-l-aristocratie-milit/translation/#p-f00fbb).",
